   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                              target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward the Black
                           Prince</ref></title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                    ><title><title><ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales"
                                    >Edward the Black Prince</ref></title>; or, the Battle of
                              Poictiers, An Historical Tragedy, In Five Acts; By <ref
                                 target="people.html#ShirleyWilliam">William Shirley</ref>, Esq. As
                              Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane"
                                 >Drury Lane</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers From
                              the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs"
                                 >Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman,
                        Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays,
                              Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XIV. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Man of the World</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Foundling</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Gamester</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Roman
                              Father</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward the Black
                                 Prince</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst,
                        Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play
                        was staged at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury
                           Lane</ref> on January 6<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1750. Laura DeWitt
                        and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The
                           Criticism Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><ref target="people.html#ShirleyWilliam">William Shirley</ref>, Esq. the author of
               this play, is little known but as a man well versed in commercial affairs. He was
               some time English resident at Lisbon, and was considered of deep penetration and
               knowledge in respect to the trading concerns of different nations; particularly in
               those of Great Britain and Portugal.<note><ref target="people.html#ShirleyWilliam"
                     >Shirley</ref> was a renowned merchant and expert on international commerce. He
                  lived in Lisbon, the capital of Portugal, for many years, as that was the center
                  of many of his commercial affairs.</note></p>

            <p>His name, as a poet, has not attained the same reputation as his skill in commerce;
               for, though he has produced many dramas, <title><ref
                     target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward the Black Prince</ref></title>
               is the only one, which has been acted of many years; nor does this tragedy possess
               much dramatic merit beyond the interest of the story.<note><title><ref
                        target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward the Black
                     Prince</ref></title> was <ref target="people.html#ShirleyWilliam"
                  >Shirley</ref>'s only successful play. Many of his other theatrical works were
                  banned from being performed due to their politically controversial
               content.</note></p>

            <p>The hero of Cressy and Poictiers must ever command the fixed attention of an English
               audience; and the reader of this play may not be displeased at having his memory
               revived on the subject of this great prince, by a short extract from history previous
               to its perusal. <quote><ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward, Prince
                     of Wales</ref>, commonly called the <ref
                     target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Black Prince</ref>, from the colour of
                  his armour, was the son of <ref target="people.html#EdwardIIIKingofEngland">Edward
                     III</ref>. and born in 1330. He accompanied his father to France when he was
                  but sixteen years old, and distinguished himself there above all the warriors of
                  his age, particularly at the battle of Cressy, where he took the standard of the
                     <ref target="people.html#JohnKingofBohemia">King of</ref>
                  <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/><ref
                     target="people.html#JohnKingofBohemia">Bohemia</ref>, embroidered with three
                  ostrich feathers, and having this motto, Ich Dien&#8212;<hi rendition="#italics">I
                     serve</hi>. This he always wore; and it has continued to be the crest of the
                     <ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince of Wales</ref> ever
                     since.<note>The source of this quotation is unidentified at present. In 1346,
                        <ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince Edward</ref> commanded
                     the English forces at the Battle of Crécy in northern France as part of the
                     Hundred Years' War.</note></quote></p>

            <p>The battle of Poictiers, in which greater feats were achieved than at Cressy, is very
               faithfully described in the following play, or, at least, all those events in which
               the <ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Black Prince</ref> was himself
               concerned in his military capacity.<note>The play takes place during the Battle of
                  Poitiers, fought by the English and French forces in west-central France in 1356,
                  also part of the Hundred Years' War. It was during this battle that <ref
                     target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince Edward</ref> obtained his most
                  famous victory.</note></p>

            <p>The character of Arnold, his love, and its ignominious effects, are the invention of
               the author to give variety to his production.<note>In the present play, Arnold is an
                  English soldier and attendent of <ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales"
                     >Prince Edward</ref>. Arnold falls in love with Mariana, the daughter of a
                  French commander and prisoner in the English camp, and out of love for her defects
                  to fight for the French for a time. Arnold eventually returns to fight for the
                  English and is absolved by <ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince
                     Edward</ref> before dying from a combat wound.</note> But the coincidence of
               names between this British renegade and an American General who betrayed his post,
               and came over to the English army during the late war in America, confers some tokens
               of the prophetic upon the writer's pen.<note>Here <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> alludes to the story of <ref
                     target="people.html#ArnoldBenedict">Benedict Arnold</ref>.</note></p>

            <p>This tragedy made its first appearance at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                  Lane</ref> in the year 1750; and as its reception was by no means flattering to
               the author, or advantageous to the manager, it sunk into obscurity, till <ref
                  target="people.html#KembleJohn">Mr. Kemble</ref> chose <ref
                  target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince Edward</ref> for the second part
               in which to appear before a London audience.<note>This play was well-received,
                  initially running for nine nights in January of 1750. <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> mistakenly draws the notion of
                  the play's poor reception from <ref target="people.html#BakerDavid">David Erskine
                     Baker</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Companion to the
                        Play-House</title></hi> (1764, p. unnumbered)&#8212;of <ref
                     target="people.html#HoperRachael">Rachael Hoper</ref>'s 1748 play of the same
                  title, <ref target="people.html#BakerDavid">Baker</ref> writes: "The Author being
                  a Woman, and entirely unused to Writing, this Play prov'd as bad as [<ref
                     target="people.html#ShirleyWilliam">Shirley</ref>'s], and being ushered into
                  the World under such terrible Disadvantages, died in the Birth, and was entirely
                  lost in its original Obscurity." <ref target="people.html#KembleJohn">John Philip
                     Kemble</ref> successfully revived the play on October 20<hi rendition="#sup"
                     >th</hi>, 1783, at which point he assumed the role of <ref
                     target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince Edward</ref>.</note> This was
               in the year 1783, and at that time, <ref target="people.html#ArnoldBenedict">General
                  Arnold</ref>, not long arrived from his hostile country, resided in this
               metropolis, a pensioner on the English government for betraying his own.</p>

            <p>It was said, that the <ref target="people.html#ArnoldBenedict">General</ref>,
               unacquainted with the fictitious events in this play, was unfortunately in the
               theatre on the first night of its revival. Whether this was a truth or not, it is
               certain, that in the scenes between Arnold and Ribemont,<note>In the present play,
                  Lord Ribemont is a marshall of the French army and delivers the fatal blow to
                  Arnold in the final act.</note> in the beginning of the <pb n="5"/>third
               act&#8212;and in that between Arnold and <ref
                  target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Edward</ref> in the fourth, a singular
               whisper ran through the whole audience, which denoted, that if they did not see the
               real <ref target="people.html#ArnoldBenedict">Arnold</ref>, at least they thought of
               him.</p>

            <p>The character of <ref target="people.html#AudleyJames">Audley</ref> has history for
               its foundation, and seems to be a precise recorder of facts. <quote><ref
                     target="people.html#AudleyJames">James, Lord Audley,</ref> of Haleigh in
                  Staffordshire, distinguished himself greatly under <ref
                     target="people.html#EdwardIIIKingofEngland">Edward III</ref>. in France, and
                  was one of the first Knights of the Garter. He was present at the famous battle of
                  Poictiers, where he was so grievously wounded, that his esquires were obliged to
                  bear him out of the field of battle; after which, the <ref
                     target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Black Prince</ref> bestowed on him a
                  noble pension, with many marks of his regard.</quote></p>

            <p><hi rendition="#flushRight">B<hi rendition="#smcaps">iog</hi>. B<hi
                     rendition="#smcaps">rit</hi>.<note>Slightly altered quotation from <ref
                        target="people.html#OldysWilliam">William Oldys</ref>' <hi
                        rendition="#italics"><title>Biographia Britannica; or, the Lives of the Most
                           Eminent Persons Who Have Flourished in Great Britain and Ireland, from
                           the Earliest Ages, Down to the Present Times</title></hi> (1747, vol. I,
                     pp. 278-279). <ref target="people.html#AudleyJames">Audley</ref> was indeed
                     gravely wounded during the Battle of Poictiers and carried from the scene to
                     the royal tent, where <ref target="people.html#EdwardPrinceofWales">Prince
                        Edward</ref> commended him as his bravest knight and offered him an annuity
                     of 500 marks.</note></hi></p>
            <lb/>
            <p>Ribemont appears to have been a creature of the poet's fancy, which should likewise
               have been exercised in giving birth to a female of much more importance than Mariana;
               for without a very interesting woman's part, few plays will be attractive.<fw
                  type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw></p>
         </div>
